{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-13T02:14:11Z", "url": "https://finance.yahoo.com/news/returns-carlo-rino-group-berhad-021411073.html", "publishedAt": "2025-04-13T02:14:11Z", "content": "If we want to find a potential multi-bagger, often there are underlying trends that can provide clues. Typically, we'll want to notice a trend of growing return on capital employed (ROCE) and alongsi… [+3575 chars]", "title": "Returns At Carlo Rino Group Berhad (KLSE:CARLORINO) Are On The Way Up", "fullContent": "If we want to find a potential multi-bagger, often there are underlying trends that can provide clues. Typically, we'll want to notice a trend of growing return on capital employed (ROCE) and alongside that, an expanding base of capital employed. Put simply, these types of businesses are compounding machines, meaning they are continually reinvesting their earnings at ever-higher rates of return. Speaking of which, we noticed some great changes in Carlo Rino Group Berhad's (KLSE:CARLORINO) returns on capital, so let's have a look.\n\nWe've found 21 US stocks that are forecast to pay a dividend yield of over 6% next year. See the full list for free.\n\nReturn On Capital Employed (ROCE): What Is It?\n\nJust to clarify if you're unsure, ROCE is a metric for evaluating how much pre-tax income (in percentage terms) a company earns on the capital invested in its business. To calculate this metric for Carlo Rino Group Berhad, this is the formula:\n\nReturn on Capital Employed = Earnings Before Interest and Tax (EBIT) ÷ (Total Assets - Current Liabilities)\n\n0.14 = RM26m ÷ (RM202m - RM16m) (Based on the trailing twelve months to December 2024).\n\nTherefore, Carlo Rino Group Berhad has an ROCE of 14%. In absolute terms, that's a satisfactory return, but compared to the Specialty Retail industry average of 10% it's much better.\n\nCheck out our latest analysis for Carlo Rino Group Berhad\n\nKLSE:CARLORINO Return on Capital Employed April 13th 2025\n\nHistorical performance is a great place to start when researching a stock so above you can see the gauge for Carlo Rino Group Berhad's ROCE against it's prior returns. If you'd like to look at how Carlo Rino Group Berhad has performed in the past in other metrics, you can view this free graph of Carlo Rino Group Berhad's past earnings, revenue and cash flow .\n\nWhat The Trend Of ROCE Can Tell Us\n\nInvestors would be pleased with what's happening at Carlo Rino Group Berhad. The data shows that returns on capital have increased substantially over the last five years to 14%. The company is effectively making more money per dollar of capital used, and it's worth noting that the amount of capital has increased too, by 87%. This can indicate that there's plenty of opportunities to invest capital internally and at ever higher rates, a combination that's common among multi-baggers.\n\nThe Key Takeaway\n\nIn summary, it's great to see that Carlo Rino Group Berhad can compound returns by consistently reinvesting capital at increasing rates of return, because these are some of the key ingredients of those highly sought after multi-baggers. Since the stock has returned a staggering 343% to shareholders over the last five years, it looks like investors are recognizing these changes. Therefore, we think it would be worth your time to check if these trends are going to continue."}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-13T11:00:03Z", "url": "https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/m4-macbook-air-vs-m3-ipad-air/", "publishedAt": "2025-04-13T11:00:03Z", "content": "Apples M4 MacBook Air and M3 iPad Air are two standout devices, each tailored to meet distinct user needs. While they share some similarities in design philosophy and quality, their differences in pe… [+7047 chars]", "title": "M4 MacBook Air vs. M3 iPad Air – Which Device Fits Your Life?", "fullContent": "Apple’s M4 MacBook Air and M3 iPad Air are two standout devices, each tailored to meet distinct user needs. While they share some similarities in design philosophy and quality, their differences in performance, functionality, and intended use cases make them suitable for different workflows. Choosing the right device depends on understanding what each offers and how it aligns with your specific requirements. The video below from GregsGadgets compares the two devices.\n\nDesign and Build: Laptop vs. Tablet\n\nThe M4 MacBook Air features Apple’s signature clamshell design, combining a lightweight yet durable aluminum build. It includes a full-size keyboard with Touch ID for secure logins, a spacious trackpad, and two USB-C ports with Thunderbolt support. Available in 13.6-inch and 15.3-inch sizes, it caters to users who prefer larger screens for productivity and multitasking. Its slim profile and fanless design make it both portable and silent during operation.\n\nIn contrast, the M3 iPad Air is a tablet-first device, designed for maximum portability. Its ultra-slim and lightweight build makes it easy to carry, and it supports the Magic Keyboard for a laptop-like experience. However, adding accessories like the Magic Keyboard and Apple Pencil increases its weight and thickness, reducing its portability advantage. The iPad Air’s design is ideal for users who value the ability to switch seamlessly between tablet and laptop modes, offering flexibility for both casual and creative tasks.\n\nDisplay Features: Touchscreen vs. Traditional\n\nBoth devices feature Liquid Retina displays with P3 wide color and True Tone technology, making sure vibrant visuals and accurate color reproduction. However, the iPad Air stands out with its touchscreen functionality and compatibility with Apple Pencil. These features make it an excellent choice for artists, designers, and users who prefer hands-on interaction for tasks like sketching, note-taking, or photo editing.\n\nThe MacBook Air, while offering larger display options, lacks touchscreen capabilities. This may be a limitation for users accustomed to direct screen interaction. However, its traditional laptop display is optimized for tasks like typing, coding, and extended reading, making it a strong choice for productivity-focused users.\n\nPerformance: M4 vs. M3\n\nPerformance is a key differentiator between these devices. The M4 MacBook Air is powered by Apple’s latest M4 chip, delivering superior CPU, GPU, and memory performance. With 16GB of memory as standard, it excels in demanding tasks such as video editing, software development, and heavy multitasking. Its advanced thermal management ensures consistent performance even during prolonged use.\n\nThe M3 iPad Air, while still powerful, runs on the older M3 chip and includes 8GB of memory. It is well-suited for casual use, creative tasks, and light productivity, such as browsing, streaming, and basic photo editing. However, it may struggle with more intensive workflows, making it less ideal for professionals who require high-performance computing.\n\nPortability and Connectivity: Mobility vs. Longevity\n\nThe iPad Air excels in portability. Its lightweight design and optional 5G cellular connectivity make it an excellent choice for users who are frequently on the move. Whether you’re traveling, working remotely, or attending meetings, the iPad Air ensures seamless connectivity without relying solely on Wi-Fi networks.\n\nThe MacBook Air, while lacking cellular connectivity, compensates with better battery life. It offers 10 to 14 hours of usage, compared to the iPad Air’s 7 to 8 hours. This makes the MacBook Air a dependable choice for extended work sessions, particularly for users who prioritize uninterrupted productivity over mobility.\n\nAudio and Camera: Media vs. Versatility\n\nThe MacBook Air features a superior speaker system, delivering richer and more immersive sound quality. This makes it an excellent option for media consumption, video calls, and audio editing. Its three-microphone array ensures clear audio capture, enhancing the overall experience for professional and personal use.\n\nThe iPad Air, on the other hand, includes a rear camera, adding versatility for tasks like document scanning, photography, and creative projects. This feature is particularly useful for artists, educators, and professionals who rely on visual content creation. While its speakers are adequate for casual use, they don’t match the MacBook Air’s audio quality.\n\nOperating Systems: macOS vs. iPadOS\n\nThe choice between macOS and iPadOS is a critical factor in deciding which device is right for you. macOS, available on the MacBook Air, is a robust and flexible operating system designed for professional workflows. It supports a wide range of software, advanced multitasking, and desktop-class applications, making it ideal for productivity-focused users.\n\niPadOS, while simpler and more intuitive, is tailored for casual users and creatives. Its touch-friendly interface and app ecosystem cater to those who prioritize ease of use and creative applications. However, its limitations in multitasking and software compatibility may be a drawback for users who require a full desktop experience.\n\nValue and Pricing: What’s Worth Your Investment?\n\nWhen evaluating value, the MacBook Air often emerges as the better option. It offers more memory, storage, and performance at a similar price point. In contrast, the iPad Air becomes significantly more expensive when paired with accessories like the Magic Keyboard and Apple Pencil, narrowing the price gap between the two devices.\n\nFor users who need a full laptop experience, the MacBook Air provides better overall value. However, for those who prioritize portability, touch interaction, and creative flexibility, the iPad Air remains a compelling choice despite its higher accessory costs.\n\nWhich Device Is Right for You?\n\nThe M4 MacBook Air is the ideal choice for users who need a powerful, versatile laptop for professional tasks. Its superior performance, larger display options, and robust operating system make it a reliable companion for productivity, multitasking, and demanding workflows.\n\nThe M3 iPad Air, on the other hand, is best suited for users who prioritize portability, touch interaction, and creative applications. Its lightweight design, touchscreen functionality, and Apple Pencil support make it an excellent choice for artists, designers, and casual users.\n\nUltimately, the decision comes down to your specific needs and priorities. If you require a traditional laptop for professional use, the MacBook Air is the clear winner. However, if you value flexibility, mobility, and hands-on interaction, the iPad Air might be the better fit. Carefully consider your workflow and lifestyle to ensure your investment aligns with your goals.\n\nExplore further guides and articles from our vast library that you may find relevant to your interests in M4 MacBook Air.\n\nSource & Image Credit: GregsGadgets\n\n\n\nLatest Geeky Gadgets Deals\n\nSome of our articles include affiliate links. If you buy something through one of these links, Geeky Gadgets may earn an affiliate commission. Learn about our Disclosure Policy"}
{"topic": "Articles", "ss": "NewsApiFeeder", "ts": "2025-04-13T14:00:17Z", "url": "http://foreignpolicy.com/2025/04/13/language-history-imperialism-russian-chinese-english-french/", "publishedAt": "2025-04-13T14:00:17Z", "content": "In the coming weeks, Flash Points will have a new name: The Reading List. Expect continued curated guides to the best articles in the magazine. Each Sunday, Ill take you on a little tour through our … [+2804 chars]", "title": "The Fight Over Language, From Haiti to Kyrgyzstan", "fullContent": "For now, let’s turn to a subject that is often overlooked in headlines of war and conquest: the imperial tool of language. The in-depth essays and reporting below explore the geopolitics of ongoing fights over language, shedding light on the cultural and linguistic dimensions of imperialism and resistance, both past and present.\n\nIn the coming weeks, Flash Points will have a new name: The Reading List. Expect continued curated guides to the best articles in the magazine. Each Sunday, I’ll take you on a little tour through our archives; on Wednesdays, my colleague Audrey Wilson will send out a companion email to help you navigate trends in the current news cycle.\n\nIn the coming weeks, Flash Points will have a new name: The Reading List. Expect continued curated guides to the best articles in the magazine. Each Sunday, I’ll take you on a little tour through our archives; on Wednesdays, my colleague Audrey Wilson will send out a companion email to help you navigate trends in the current news cycle.\n\nFor now, let’s turn to a subject that is often overlooked in headlines of war and conquest: the imperial tool of language. The in-depth essays and reporting below explore the geopolitics of ongoing fights over language, shedding light on the cultural and linguistic dimensions of imperialism and resistance, both past and present.\n\nStudents sit at desks in a classroom.\n\nThe world is long overdue for the abandonment of the unstated but powerful hegemony that exists around the great imperial languages of centuries past.\n\nA small market on Song Kul Lake, Kyrgyzstan.\n\nThe war in Ukraine is leading to a linguistic backlash in Russophone Central Asia as young people embrace their mother tongues.\n\nA Tibetan prayer flag\n\nThe diaspora is preserving Tibetan as Chinese oppression grows at home.\n\nStudents look at booklets at their desks on the first day back to school at the National School of Tabarre in the Haitian capital Port-au-Prince on Sept. 5, 2016.\n\nAround 90 percent of Haitians speak only Haitian Creole. So why is school mostly conducted in French?\n\nAbout 500 pupils and their parents protest against the language education reform in front of the parliament in Latvia on Feb 10, 2005.\n\nThe Baltic nation is taking cultural cohesion into its own hands—and risking backlash."}
